05702nam a22009495i 9780823288236DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232882367 a10.1515/97808232882362doi  a(DE-B1597)566202  a(OCoLC)1154558140  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a810.9/362231 aNeely, Michelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAgainst Sustainability :bReading Nineteenth-Century America in the Age of Climate Crisis /cMichelle Neely. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Unlikely Environmentalisms of Nineteenth- Century American Literature -- t1. Recycling Fantasies: Whitman, Clifton, and the Dream of Compost -- t2. Joyful Frugality: Thoreau, Dickinson, and the Pleasures of Not Consuming -- t3. The Problem with Preservation: Aesthetics and Sanctuary in Catlin, Parkman, Erdrich, Melville, and Byatt -- t4. Radical Pet Keeping: Crafts, Wilson, and Living with Others in the Anthropocene -- tCoda. Embracing Green Temporalities: Indigenous Sustainabilities, Anglo- American Utopias -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAgainst Sustainability responds to the twenty-first-century environmental crisis by unearthing the nineteenth-century U.S. literary, cultural, and scientific contexts that gave rise to sustainability, recycling, and preservation. Through novel pairings of antebellum and contemporary writers including Walt Whitman and Lucille Clifton, George Catlin and Louise Erdrich, and Herman Melville and A. S. Byatt, the book demonstrates that some of our most vaunted strategies to address ecological crisis in fact perpetuate environmental degradation.Yet Michelle C. Neely also reveals that the nineteenth century offers useful and generative environmentalisms, if only we know where and how to find them. Henry David Thoreau and Emily Dickinson experimented with models of joyful, anti-consumerist frugality. Hannah Crafts and Harriet Wilson devised forms of radical pet-keeping that model more just ways of living with others. Ultimately, the book explores forms of utopianism that might more reliably guide mainstream environmental culture toward transformative forms of ecological and social justice. Through new readings of familiar texts, Against Sustainability demonstrates how nineteenth-century U.S. literature can help us rethink our environmental paradigms in order to imagine more just and environmentally sound futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnvironmentalism in literature. 0aHuman ecology in literature. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings onzUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aEnvironment. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAntebellum Literature.  aAnthropocene.  aDickinson.  aEnvironmentalism.  aMelville.  aNineteenth Century.  aPreservation.  aSustainability.  aThoreau.  aWhitman.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020 Englishz978311070476108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2020z9783110704563oZDB-23-DSP08iTitl